<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Test for Bank and examiners: The appeal against closure of
Mount Banking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England faces one of the first real external tests of its
credibility as a regulator this week as a panel of three sits to assess
whether it was right almost a year ago to recommend closure of Mount
Banking.
The workings of the banking appeals tribunal - the panel before which the
Bank is appearing - are also being tested for the first time. No other
tribunal has been constituted in the six years since the legal provisions
for them were introduced.
The Bank of England faces an appeal brought by Mr Navinchandra Bhagwanji
Shah and Mr Suresh Bhagwanji Shah, the shareholders in Mount Banking, a
small bank based in the UK.
Most of Mount's depositors were Asians. Accountants at KPMG Peat Marwick who
are the administrators to the bank are also involved in the appeal.
The Shahs object to the petition brought by the Bank in early October last
year to place Mount in provisional liquidation. This was granted, and Mount
entered administration two weeks later.
Creditors last month approved a voluntary arrangement which leaves open
several options for Mount's future.
The procedure for a banking appeals tribunal was established in the 1987
Banking Act, with the details laid out in a statutory instrument which
became effective in that year.
Although seven cases have gone as far as a preliminary hearing, none has yet
reached the stage of a full appeal. 'It is an ad hoc body,' an official
familiar with the tribunal said yesterday.
'It is so long since the previous one (appeal) that we are almost
re-inventing the wheel.'
Control for administering appeals has been shifted since 1987 from the
Treasury to the Lord Chancellor's Department, where it is co-ordinated by
the secretariat responsible for value added tax and inland revenue appeals.
The same staff would also handle appeal procedures laid down in legislation
for building societies and friendly societies, though no such action has
ever been launched in either case.
When any banking appeal is received, the lord chancellor nominates a
chairman and the chancellor of the exchequer puts forward two 'wing' members
 -so called because they sit on either side of the chairman.
The chairman holds a preliminary hearing and if there is a case to answer
and those involved wish to continue, a tribunal is held. Lawyers may
represent all those called and the verdicts and identities have normally
been kept secret.
In 1989-90 there were three initial appeals which were either withdrawn or
settled without recourse to the full tribunal. One of the cases is believed
to have concerned Harrods Bank.
In the past year there have been a further three appeals. One was settled by
agreement, one was withdrawn and a decision about whether to proceed to a
full appeal on the third is still pending.
In addition, there is the Mount case, for which the chairman is Mr Jonathan
Mance QC. The wing members are Mr Christopher Swinson, an accountant, and Mr
Nicholas Clegg, a banker. The hearings started on Monday and may run into
next week.
The Bank of England rejects suggestions that the tribunal reflects a greater
willingness to have its authority as a supervisor tested - an approach
recommended in the Bingham report following the collapse of Bank of Credit
and Commerce International.
Others suggest that the fact a tribunal is taking place is more a function
of the tenaciousness of the Shahs and their insistence in pursuing the
formal procedures as far as possible.
</TEXT>
