<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Jubilee Line extension looks set for go-ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE JUBILEE Line Underground extension to Canary Wharf in east London is
almost certain to go ahead, after months of negotiations between banks and
the government over the private sector's promised Pounds 400m contribution
to the project.
A banker to the project said that all material disagreements had been
resolved.
Eleven commercial banks led by Lloyds will today announce a financial
reconstruction of Canary Wharf, which has been in administration under
insolvency procedures for more than a year. The 11 lent Pounds 600m to fund
construction.
The rescue of Canary Wharf - which was built by Olympia &amp; York of Canada,
the world's biggest property developer until it collapsed last year - has
been dependent on an agreement being reached with the government on building
the Tube extension.
Banks have been prepared to inject new funds into Canary Wharf only if they
could be confident that the Jubilee extension would be built.
As part of the reconstruction Ernst &amp; Young, the accountants acting as
administrators to the project, are providing creditors with details of a
proposed settlement of claims. If creditors accept Canary Wharf will come
out of administration under a company voluntary arrangement. It would be the
first time that a big company emerged from administration as a going
concern.
The European Investment Bank, owned by the European Community, is providing
Pounds 98m so that the first two tranches of the private sector's
contribution can be made.
Plans for the Pounds 1.7bn London Crossrail east-west rail link have run
into a delay. London Underground confirmed last night that the first meeting
of the Crossrail Bill committee, scheduled for next month, had been
postponed.
The government is continuing its search for cuts in the cost of the scheme
and has 'asked for the delay so we can look at costs', London Underground
said.
</TEXT>
