<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / TUC plea to Labour body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TUC has complained to the Geneva-based International Labour Organisation
about the British government's new legislation permitting employers to deny
pay increases to any employees who refuse to sign personal contracts, thus
requiring them to give up their rights of union representation.
Mr John Monks, TUC general secretary, said yesterday that this provision of
the Trade Union Reform and Employment Rights Act was 'a clear violation of
the key ILO convention on the right to organise and collective bargaining'.
He acknowledged that the ILO lacked the legal powers to force the government
to amend the legislation, but said that the TUC should keep up the pressure
and expose how employment rights in Britain did not match up to
international labour standards.
In recent years the ILO has upheld TUC complaints and criticised the British
government for unilaterally abolishing the negotiating rights of the
teachers' unions and failing to put an end to the blacklisting of trade
unionists by employers.
</TEXT>
