<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Pits to close after low bid turnout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRIVATE-SECTOR mining companies have bid to operate just seven of the 19
pits put out to tender by British Coal following its decision that it could
no longer run them. As a result British Coal will prepare the 12 pits that
did not receive bids for closure.
The final tally of bids is even less than was expected earlier this week
when the deadline closed for the last tranche of five pits to be put out for
licensing. This is because RJB Mining has withdrawn a bid for Easington
colliery in County Durham after it failed to agree with British Coal who
should bear the costs of pumping water in the area.
Three of the 19 mines are the subject of tenders which involve the use of
surface assets only. The low number of bids is a blow for thousands of
miners who have been made redundant, and provides little comfort for the
government as it prepares for a new round of closures.
In all, there were 19 tenders for 11 collieries but three have since been
withdrawn.
The bids involving mining proposals were led by Edwards Energy, headed by Mr
Malcolm Edwards, former British Coal commercial director, which submitted
five tenders, and RJB, which submitted four, not including Easington. Apart
from them, only two mining offers were received, both for the same pit,
Betws, in Wales.
In the final tranche of five pits only one, Coventry Colliery at Keresley,
attracted an offer which involved mining. Parkside, Sharlston, Shirebrook
and Taff Merthyr received no offers.
The withdrawal of RJB's bid for Easington will heighten concern about water
pumping in the Durham coalfield.
The National Rivers Authority this week named Easington as a mine whose
closure threatens to contaminate water supplies. British Coal said that
talks with the NRA would continue.
Redundant British Coal employees are satisfied with the career advice they
receive as part of their severance packages, a survey has found.
The study was conducted among 526 former British Coal employees recently
made redundant. Half those interviewed were already in employment or
self-employment, the majority finding a new job within six months. More than
half said the job shop and career centre run by British Coal Enterprises, a
British Coal subsidiary, contributed directly to their finding new
employment.
