<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / DTI at odds with mergers body on Gas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OFFICIALS at the Department of Trade and Industry appear to be in conflict
with the Monopolies and Mergers Commission over the best way to deal with
British Gas, company chiefs suggested yesterday.
Mr Philip Rogerson, British Gas's finance director, said that the MMC's
recommendations in its recent report ran counter to submissions made to the
Commission by the DTI's oil and gas division. 'It goes against what they
said. That's how I read it,' he said, while announcing the company's
half-year results.
Last month, the MMC recommended that British Gas be broken up by 1997, and
that its monopoly of the tariff market for small consumers be removed over
the following five years. However, publication of the full MMC report
earlier this week revealed that the DTI placed top priority on removing the
tariff market monopoly rather than the case for breaking up British Gas.
In their submission to the MMC, DTI officials said that as a free market
developed and competitors made greater inroads, the question of whether
British Gas should be broken up 'seemed likely to assume a smaller
importance than during the transition to it'. The key point was to regulate
the market in a way which enabled competitors to enter on equal terms, they
said.
A break-up would also create difficulties, the officials told the MMC. It
would require 'a radical overhaul of the legislation', and would be a
'complex exercise with its own transitional uncertainties.' They said it
would end British Gas's ability to underpin the domestic gas market during
the transition phase, and would increase the market's dependence on new
mechanisms which could not be tested in advance.
Officials also appeared to support British Gas's contention that a break-up
would prevent it competing effectively abroad, where some of its best growth
prospects lie. They told the MMC that 'the successful pursuit of overseas
gas business in existing market conditions required significant players with
live experience in all main areas of the business. There might be a balance
to be weighed up between requirements for the home market and requirements
for success abroad'.
Officials concluded with a warning that some British Gas shareholders might
see a break-up of the company as a departure from the spirit of the 1986
privatisation prospectus.
The fact that the MMC ignored these cautions and put break-up at the top of
the list will pose a dilemma for trade ministers. One option is to reverse
the MMC's recommendations and deregulate the market first, leaving break-up
till later, if at all.
One point of agreement between the MMC and the DTI is that the simultaneous
de-regulation and break-up is impractical.
British Gas is hoping that ministers will make a decision before Christmas.
Mr Cedric Brown, the chief executive, said yesterday that he wanted to avoid
a prolonged period of uncertainty.
Mr Brown said that British Gas has not yet had any contact with the DTI
about the report. In the absence of Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade
secretary, who is recovering from a heart attack, the matter is being
handled by Mr Neil Hamilton, the corporate affairs minister.
The DTI is seeking comments by the end of October.
</TEXT>
