<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Coal pension fund may be split
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is proposing to split British Coal's Pounds 13.5bn pension
assets into two separate funds for past and present employees as part of the
planned privatisation of the company.
Under proposals put forward for comment yesterday the Department of Trade
and Industry said that the needs of existing employees differed from those
of pensioners, and that the new funds should be structured accordingly.
A choice of arrangements was proposed for pensioners. They could have a
closed scheme in which the government would guarantee inflation-linked
pensions and ensure the scheme's solvency. The government would share in any
surpluses, however, and would be involved in investment decisions.
Alternatively the government would provide no guarantees, but members would
not have to share future valuation surpluses with it.
Two new pension schemes would be set up for existing employees, following
from present arrangements which have separate schemes for supervisory grades
and industrial employees.
Each scheme would be required by statute to provide the same package of
benefits as before. The new schemes would operate on an industry-wide basis.
Employees would be free to choose whether to join a scheme, take out a
personal pension or join another scheme operated by their new employer.
Only British Coal employees who were contributing members of the main
schemes up to privatisation would be able to join an industry-wide scheme.
Employers would be responsible for making good any deficits in these
schemes.
It would be up to employers to decide on the pension arrangements for people
joining the coal industry after privatisation.
Yesterday's proposals do not say how the present funds should be divided
between the new schemes.
The DTI said it would have to be satisfied that the interests of
beneficiaries, employers and the taxpayer were satisfied.
The proposals were welcomed by the trustees of the British Coal staff
superannuation scheme. They described it as 'a first step, representing very
substantial progress in meeting the concerns of our members'. much work
would be needed to reach agreement on the details, however.
The pension funds have 577,000 members, more than 95 per cent of them
current or deferred pensioners. In June there were only 29,000 contributing
employees.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Coal Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
