<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Rural petrol stations 'at risk'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NUMBER of rural petrol stations operated by large integrated oil companies
such as Shell could close if competition from hypermarkets continues
unabated, Sir John Collins, chairman and chief executive of Shell UK, said
yesterday.
Sir John said in the company's annual energy review that competitive
pressures were undermining the 'old public services undertakings' by which
the big oil companies ensured countrywide access to fuel supplies at uniform
prices. He added that the undertakings were becoming 'an untenable
anachronism'.
Sir John said that hyper-markets account for 16 per cent of national sales
of vehicle fuels. Their market share is growing rapidly because they can
take advantage of the cheap supplies from surplus capacity in British
refineries.
Hypermarkets can also concentrate on a few sites where they can incorporate
the latest health, safety and environmental standards at relatively low
costs.
'There is a growing differential between low volumes and high unit costs of
rural sites and the converse for hyper-markets who operate only at prime
sites,' Sir John said.
'These differentials can no longer be accommodated . . . (and) they will
increasingly entail the reduction and concentration of oil company networks,
with consequent pressures on the availability or price of rural petrol
supplies.'
Sir John also warned that urban motorists should not assume that the trend
towards lower petrol prices would last. Financial strains on re-finers were
now 'acute' because of a 20 per cent surplus in capacity combined with the
cost of new environmental measures, many of which he believes are
'ill-considered'.
</TEXT>
