<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Sales rise but shops peg prices, says CBI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RETAIL sales rose again last month, but shop managers still lack the
confidence to put up prices, a Confederation of British Industry survey
showed yesterday.
Speaking at the launch of the CBI's quarterly distributive trades survey, Mr
Nigel Whittaker, distributive trades panel chairman, warned that tax
increases in the November Budget could damage the 'modest recovery in high
street activity'.
The CBI said the increase in sales in August, following similar improvements
in June and July, was accompanied by the lowest year-on-year rise in shop
prices in the 10 years since the survey was first conducted.
Mr Whittaker added: 'Part of the growth in high street business may have
been achieved by retailers setting low prices to win business in competitive
market conditions.'
While the improvement in retail sales appears to be well-established, the
pace of the upturn is uneven.
The survey showed a patchy recovery across sectors. Some traders reported
small sales rises and, in general, retailers with just one store had trade
volumes below last year's levels. Motor traders had their best August for
five years.
The outlook for wholesalers was unpromising. They reported a slowdown in
activity since spring and expect sales growth over the next three months to
fall further.
The strongest improvements were in clothing, furniture and carpet shops.
Sales for grocers, shoe shops and chemists were also buoyant.
A balance of 31 per cent of retailers reported increased sales in the year
to August, compared with 32 and 30 per cent in July and June.
