<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Israel and Palestinians End Hostility: Aid needed at a
proper pace
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON, LIONEL BARBER, WILL DAWKINS and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS, TOKYO, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PENS are set to be uncapped for the signature by Israel and the Palestinians
of an outline agreement on self-rule. Donors are already addressing the
question of what aid will be needed to create a functioning Palestinian
administration, and an economy integrated with those of its neighbours and
the wider world.
European Community foreign ministers tomorrow will consider plans for an
Ecu500m (Pounds 383m) aid package to the West Bank and Gaza Strip - a
package aimed to capitalise on the historic breakthrough by Israel and the
Palestinians and to consolidate the EC's importance as a donor and trade
partner in the Middle East.
Scandinavian countries last week pledged Dollars 140m in aid to the
territories over the next four years. The US is seeking to 'facilitate
contributions' to the new Palestinian authority, but administration
officials have made clear that they do not expect to be the principal source
of finance.
Japan 'would have to help with restructuring in the region' once the accord
was signed, Mr Tsutomu Hata, foreign minister, said yesterday.
In total, according to estimates based on a draft World Bank report and the
views of other economists, the new Palestinian 'entity' will require
external financing, both in aid and private capital flows, of more than
Dollars 4bn in the next decade.
This sum, according to Mr Stanley Fisher, a Massachusetts Institute of
Technology professor who helped produce a Harvard University report on the
economy of the territories, represents the likely maximum the Gaza Strip and
West Bank could absorb.
'No running economy can take in more than about 10 per cent of GDP,' he
says, putting the combined annual gross domestic product of the West Bank
and Gaza strip at about Dollars 4bn.
This would also be a greater sum of aid, proportionate to the size of the
territories' economies, than the original post-war Marshall Plan for Europe.
Most to the point, according to several economists, such a sum is likely to
place Gaza and the West Bank - if adeptly managed - on a sound economic
footing. 'All the ingredients for growth are there,' says Mr Fisher.
As important as the gross sums of aid, however, will be the promptness and
co-ordination of their disbursement.
As a first step, officials from the PLO, Israel and its Arab neighbours will
meet in Washington on September 20 to discuss creating a central fund to
direct international assistance, under the World Bank, whose economists have
already created a detailed plan for regional economic development. The Bank
can lend only to member countries but is seeking ways around this hurdle for
the territories.
Swift as the initial response of the EC, the World Bank and others has been,
shadows hang over co-ordination of the international aid effort. It is
unclear, for instance, how the EC package will be aligned with wider
international attempts to create a viable economy in the territories, with
proper roads, water, and telecommunications.
Japan has already contacted the EC about the Brussels plan, but senior EC
officials say there has so far been no contact with the US.
What already looks clear, however, is the determination of donors to help
this historic opportunity succeed - not simply in creating a viable economy
for a Palestinian proto-state, but in encouraging both better Middle Eastern
development and the closer integration of the region's economies with, in
particular, those of the EC.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ILZ  Israel, Middle East.
</CN>
<XX>
