FT  10 SEP 93 / Olympique Marseille ban delayed by court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIQUE MARSEILLE, the troubled French football club, yesterday won the
first round in its legal battle against exclusion from the European
Champions' Cup when a Swiss court temporarily suspended the ban, pending a
final ruling, reports Alice Rawsthorn from Paris.
Mr Bernard Tapie, the flamboyant French businessman and Socialist former
minister who chairs the club, vowed to stay on as chairman.
The Marseille club, which last season became the first French team to win
the European Champions' Cup, is fighting to overturn the decision on Monday
by Uefa, the European football authority, to ban it from this season's
competition because of a bribery scandal. Club officials have been accused
of trying to bribe players of a rival French team to rig a league match last
season.
The ban threatened to drive Olympique Marseille into bankruptcy because of
the loss of the estimated FFr150m (Pounds 17m) the club had expected from
its European games. A final court ruling on the Uefa ban is expected within
days.
The club's position is further complicated by an edict earlier yesterday
from Fifa, the world football authority, that it be suspended from the
French league unless it abandons its legal battle against the Uefa ban.
