<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Israel and PLO agree to peace: Recognition achieved as
leaders exchange letters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL and the Palestine Liberation Organisation, bitter enemies for nearly
three decades, recognised each other yesterday in a decision which will
enable the signing of an historic peace accord between the two parties in
Washington next week.
Israel said Mr Yitzhak Rabin, prime minister, would sign a letter to Mr
Yassir Arafat, PLO chairman, in a public ceremony this morning after
receiving two letters signed by Mr Arafat last night in Tunis.
The Arafat letters, which were approved by the PLO executive, were being
ferried from Tunis to Jerusalem by Mr Johan Joergen Holst, the Norwegian
foreign minister, who played a critical role in the Israeli-PLO dialogue.
In a letter to Mr Rabin, Mr Arafat commits the PLO to recognising the Jewish
state's right to exist in peace and security, to a peaceful resolution of
all future conflict, to a renunciation of terrorism and violence and to
convening the Palestinian parliament-in-exile to amend its founding charter
which denies Israel's right to exist.
In the second letter, addressed to Mr Holst, Mr Arafat says that after
Monday's signing of an Israeli-Palestinian peace accord on self-government
for the occupied-West Bank and Gaza Strip, he will call on the 1.9m
residents of the Israeli-occupied territories to suspend the intifada - the
six-year-old Palestinian uprising.
Mr Rabin's letter to Mr Arafat says: 'The government of Israel has decided
to recognise the PLO as the representative of the Palestinian people and
commence negotiations with the PLO within the Middle East peace process.'
The letter marks the abandonment of years of virulent Israeli hostility to
the PLO, which it had branded a terrorist organisation bent upon the
destruction of the Jewish state.
The move paves the way for an end to a conflict marked by terrorism,
assassinations, hijackings and violence committed by one side or the other
since the PLO was set up in 1964. It also paves the way for the first
durable peace between Jews and Arabs. in the Holy Land and the beginnings of
a Palestinian homeland. Earlier, Mr Rabin told Labour party MPs that Mr
Arafat would tell the residents of the occupied territories that 'a new era
has begun, an era of reconciliation, building and co-operation, and
especially opposition to terror and violence'.
Mr Moshe Shahal, Israeli police minister, and Mr Holst said separately that
a broader agreement on Palestinian self-rule, including immediate Israeli
military withdrawal from Gaza and the West Bank town of Jericho, initialled
in Norway three weeks ago, could now be signed in Washington on Monday. A US
official said the ceremony was set for 11am at the White House.
Mr Arafat said he would attend the signing if he was invited by President
Bill Clinton to the ceremony. Mr Shimon Peres, Israel's foreign minister,
who clinched the peace deal, is expected to sign for the Jewish state. Mr
Arafat is currently barred from entering the US after Washington cut
contacts with the liberation movement in 1990. Mr Clinton, however, said
yesterday the US would now consider resuming dialogue with the PLO 'if the
PLO statement . . . meets the criteria we have repeatedly set down:
renouncing terrorism and acknowledging Israel's right to exist'.
Both Mr Peres and Mr Arafat appeared in an unprecedented live connection on
French Television. 'This is really an historical change after 100 years of
war, Holocaust and victims,' Mr Peres said.
Yesterday's breakthrough on mutual recognition follows days of secret and
difficult negotiations in Paris over how to word the letters. The PLO was
concerned about Israel's demand that it suspend the intifada.
The text was finally nailed down between Mr Uri Savir, director-general of
Israel's foreign ministry and Mr Ahmed Qurie (Abu Ala), head of the PLO
economics section, after it was agreed Mr Arafat could send a second letter
to Mr Holst which specifically avoids using the word intifada.
In Israel there were signs that virulent right-wing opposition to the
agreement was waning. Mr Ariel Sharon, one of Israel's most uncompromising
hawks, said the right wing led by the Likud party should accept that the
peace agreement was irreversible.
Israel and Palestinians, Page 4
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ILZ  Israel, Middle East.
</CN>
<XX>
