<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 93 / Major puts down revolt by right wing over taxation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent and ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour
Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR, the prime minister, yesterday sought to exert his authority
on the government by facing down a right-wing revolt on taxation and warning
ministers not to step out of line in future.
In a robust lecture to the first cabinet meeting for six weeks, Mr Major
warned that grass roots Conservative activists were fed up with government
disunity.
He said the government must unite around agreed policies and draw a line
under the battering it has sustained since its unexpected victory in the
1992 general election.
The message was rammed home by Sir Norman Fowler, the Conservative party
chairman, who reported on soundings taken from more than 150 constituency
chairmen in the past week.
Sir Norman said regional officials were desperate for a renewed sense of
unity in the party, and tired of the splits and recriminations of the past
year.
He also confirmed the party's decision to concentrate its resources on
fighting the growing threat posed by the Liberal Democrats in the south and
south-west of England.
Rightwing hopes of heading off the possibility of tax increases in the
November budget were torpedoed in a forthright intervention by Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor.
Mr Clarke forestalled any challenge to his budget strategy by saying all
options remain open and ruling out a renegotiation of next year's agreed
spending total.
His vigorous defence of the chancellor's traditional right to control
budget-making silenced rightwing ministers, who judged it prudent to drop
plans to air the taxation issue.
However, Mr Clarke pleased rightwingers in a speech to the CBI in Glasgow,
in which he reaffirmed the government's determination to cut spending in the
long term and promised a second year of tough controls on public sector pay.
'I have read some mistaken speculation that I might relax on the public pay
front. Do not worry,' the chancellor said. 'We need to see the current pay
realism continue.'
Trade union leaders at the TUC conference in Brighton were dismayed. Some
warned of industrial action if the government tried to tighten this year's
1.5 per cent limit on pay rises.
Mr Alan Jinkinson , general secretary of Unison, the public service union,
said he had no doubt about the 'serious consequences' of another year of
imposed pay policy: 'Public service workers have already paid an unfair
price for the government's inept mismanagement of the economy.'
Most of the cabinet discussion took place at a one and a half hour meeting -
held without officials - which followed a formal half-hour official cabinet
meeting restricted largely to administrative matters.
The tone of the debate reflects Mr Major's determination to exert a firmer
grip on the government, which he believes can revive its popularity in line
with economic recovery.
However, rightwing backbenchers continued to claim that any increases in tax
would be suicidal for the government.
The tax nettle, Page 6
Joe Rogaly, Page 18
</TEXT>
