<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / (CORRECTED) Global union watch on Hanson
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 17th September 1993) appended to this article.
A WORLDWIDE trade union council is to be established representing workers
employed by companies owned by Hanson, the conglomerate.
This was announced yesterday after a meeting of TUC leaders with the
AFL-CIO, the US trade union body, and the United Mineworkers of America.
The council will be permanent with worker representatives worldwide. The aim
is to co-ordinate union strategy across the Hanson subsidiaries.
The TUC and AFL-CIO said they would be seeking a meeting with the company to
discuss creating a joint company-union council.
Yesterday's announcement is the latest response to the current strike in the
US by miners, including 17,000 employed by Peabody, the biggest private coal
company in the US and a wholly owned Hanson subsidiary. The protest, which
has been going on since February, is against the Bituminous Coal Association
of which Peabody is a member. The United Mineworkers of America are
demanding that jobs should be offered to unionised miners in new pits when
exhausted ones are closed.
The strike has turned into a bitter struggle over the future of trade
unionism in the US coal industry. As the leading negotiator in the
mineowners' association, Peabody is setting the pace for non-unionism in an
industry where two-thirds of the 100,000 miners are still organised.
The close involvement of the TUC and the AFL-CIO reflects a growing
partnership across the Atlantic. They want to establish more global
organisations to press for the establishment of social clauses established
by the International Labour Organisation and the OECD in agreements with
global corporations.
Mr Martin Taylor, vice-chairman of Hanson, made no comment about the
proposal for a joint company-union council. He said: 'We have excellent
industrial relations.'
MSF, the technical union, has announced what it calls a US-style corporate
campaign against Zurich Insurance company over its decision to de-recognise
the union. MSF has 1,000 members employed by Municipal Mutual Insurance,
which was acquired by Zurich earlier this year.
The campaign involves legal action, local and national lobbying, and
advertising.
CORRECTION
ON September 9 the FT wrote that Mutual Municipal Insurance had been
acquired by Zurich Insurance early this year. Zurich Insurance has in fact
only acquired parts of the business of MMI.
</TEXT>
