FT  09 SEP 93 / International Company News: Air NZ profits advance as route
revenue climbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AIR New Zealand yesterday announced a 21.2 per cent increase in profits to
NZDollars 139.5m (USDollars 76.6m) for the year ended June, helped by higher
revenue on its routes to Asia, the US and Europe.
Directors said that while the airline continued to outperform most of its
international competitors, returns were still less than needed to
appropriately reward shareholders and finance growth.
The profit was some NZDollars 15m higher than analysts had been expecting,
and the improvement was unexpectedly helped by abnormal gains of NZDollars
3.7m. Last year the airline reported abnormal losses of NZDollars 13.1m.
Air NZ, whose major shareholders are Brierley Investments and Qantas,
reported operating earnings of NZDollars 140.3m, against NZDollars 134.3m.
Equity accounted losses of associates were NZDollars 4.5m, against NZDollars
6m.
Directors said that the group was budgeting for further growth in passenger
traffic on Asian routes. However, it expected little if any growth on
internal routes or services to Australia and only modest growth in the UK,
Europe and US traffic.
The company said it had successfully handled an increase in 8.9 per cent in
additional capacity.
The dividend is being maintained at an unchanged six cents a share, bringing
the total to 10 cents this year.
