<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / International Company News: Siemens unit makes first profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE German electronics group Siemens said its Automotive Systems Group will
make a small profit in the year ending September 30 for the first time since
it was founded in 1984, Reuter reports from Frankfurt.
Mr Juergen Mache, board member in the division, told a news conference
1992/93 earnings were barely above break-even point, but said Siemens did
not give figures for its different business sectors.
Mr Franz Wressnigg, division chairman, said it expected a 'comparatively
modest business result' for 1992/93.
Despite a worldwide sales slump in the car industry and increasing price
pressures on suppliers, orders received will reach last year's DM2.6bn
(Dollars 1.56bn) while sales will increase to slightly over the DM2.5bn seen
in 1991/92, Mr Wressnigg said.
The division had made losses in recent years, he added.
Domestic business had levelled off, although foreign business was growing as
the US market improved, Mr Wressnigg said. In Siemens' core area of
automotive electronics it saw solid growth this year, with unit sales of
anti-lock braking system electronics more than doubling.
Research and development expenditure, currently some 12 per cent of sales,
had grown slightly, while the workforce of over 13,000 had remained steady.
A company spokesman said Siemens' group turnover in the traffic and
transport sectors overall amounted to DM8bn, some 10 per cent of group
sales.
The group also said it was expanding its automotive systems production
facilities in the Czech Republic and Slovakia and hoped to open a plant for
heating and air-conditioning systems in the Czech city of Rakovnik.
</TEXT>
