<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / International Company News: Total fends off European
recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TOTAL, the French oil group, yesterday announced a modest decline in net
profits, to FFr1.8bn (Dollars 317.5m) from FFr1.9bn for the first half of
1993. The result underlines its resilience to recession in Europe.
Turnover dipped from FFr68.76bn to FFr67.85bn, in what the company described
as a difficult economic environment. Operating income profits, however, rose
slightly from FFr3.4bn to FFr3.49bn.
'It was a good result given the economic background,' said Mr John
Wellemeyer, oil industry analyst at Morgan Stanley. He forecast net profits
of about FFr3.6bn for the full year.
Mr Serge Tchuruk, chairman of Total, said the results reflected a varied
performance across the group's core businesses, and that the benefits of its
'refocusing' strategy, launched in 1990, would start to be felt from next
year.
He said the group had begun to seek alliances in gas distribution and
electricity supply, and that this presented strong growth opportunities.
In the first six months, the exploration and production division was hit by
the decline in crude oil prices, from Dollars 19 per barrel to about Dollars
18.20. As a result, operating income fell to FFr1.19bn from FFr1.31bn in the
first half of 1992.
Oil production, excluding the Middle East, fell from 154,000 to 135,000
barrels per day. Gas production also fell, from 972m to 941m cu ft. per day.
Total said the reductions reflected the impact of disposals. New
developments in the second half would offset these declines.
Its 1992 forecast for production growth of 50 per cent between 1990 and 1995
remained unaffected, the group said.
The chemicals division, affected by the European recession and the downturn
in the automotive and construction industries, also saw profits decline.
Operating profits fell to FFr753m from FFr852m.
The trading and Middle East division increased operating profits from
FFr304m to FFr434m, reflecting an improvement in shipping rates in the first
six months of the year.
Mr Tchuruk also raised the prospect of a further sale of the French state's
holding in the oil group. Although the government has said it wants to
maintain its stake in Total at about 5 per cent, the effects of capital
increases during the year have raised this to 8 per cent.
The sale of the surplus 3 per cent, which is valued at about FFr2bn, could
be made at any time, he said.
</TEXT>
