FT  09 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Vardon Pounds 0.5m in the black
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
VARDON, the leisure company which owns Sea Life Centres and The London
Dungeon and came to the market in October 1992, made pre-tax profits of
Pounds 540,000 in the six months to June 30, against restated losses of
Pounds 282,000.
The interim dividend is raised from 0.25p to 0.3p.
Turnover at the visitor attractions division grew to Pounds 5.44m (Pounds
3.15m), giving operating profits of Pounds 539,000 (Pounds 302,000). Three
new attractions were added during the period - the Seal Sanctuary in
Cornwall was bought in February and Sea Life Centres in Southend, Essex, and
Scheveningen, the Netherlands, were opened in May. The London Dungeon was
refurbished and now includes the Jack the Ripper Experience. Capital
expenditure totalled Pounds 3.9m in the period.
The group's 10 bingo clubs, acquired in May, traded for seven weeks within
the group and contributed turnover of Pounds 1.02m and operating profits of
Pounds 99,000.
Group turnover was Pounds 6.45m (Pounds 3.75m). Earnings worked through at
0.7p (losses 0.9p).
