<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Charles Baynes advances to Pounds 3.27m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHARLES Baynes, which yesterday announced a rise in pre-tax profits from
Pounds 1.88m to Pounds 3.27m for the first half of 1993, is to expand its
distribution side with the acquisition of Buck &amp; Hickman from P&amp;O for a
maximum of Pounds 32.48m cash.
'We love distribution businesses,' said Mr John Perkins, finance director,
adding that any company would like to acquire well and independently run,
cash-generative businesses from larger groups returning to their cores.
B&amp;H, a distributor of engineers' tools, consumables and equipment in the UK,
will keep its present management and will operate on a stand-alone basis
within Baynes.
The purchase will be funded by the issue of some 34.5m 5.8p (net)
mandatorily convertible preference shares at 100p each to raise about Pounds
33.3m net. They are convertible at 69p per share and will be available in an
open offer to ordinary shareholders on a 1-for-4 basis. SG Warburg will
subscribe for any shares not taken up in the offer.
Mr Perkins said that with an acquisition of this size, Baynes wanted the net
profits of B&amp;H to service the preference shares. In 1992, it made operating
profits of Pounds 3.5m on turnover of Pounds 48.2m. At the end of 1992, its
tangible assets were Pounds 20.3m; after deducting dividends to P&amp;O and
before an intra-group loan note of about Pounds 11m that Baynes is also
acquiring, assets will fall to Pounds 15.5m at October 2.
Mr Perkins said that Baynes' balance sheet would remain strong: after the
buy shareholders' funds will stand at about Pounds 40m after some Pounds 17m
goodwill write-off from B&amp;H.
Group operating profits in the half grew to Pounds 3.09m (Pounds 1.62m) on
turnover up at Pounds 39.3m (Pounds 37.2m). Acquisitions in the period
contributed Pounds 735,000 and Pounds 7.52m respectively. On an annualised
basis continuing businesses made profits of Pounds 2.36m (Pounds 1.52m) on
turnover flat at Pounds 31.8m. Margins were improved through job losses and
Baynes capital expenditure programmes.
The interim dividend is lifted to 0.575p (0.525p), payable from adjusted
earnings of 1.65p (1.05p) per share.
</TEXT>
