<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / Soros buys into US property
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A US property fund set up earlier this year by George Soros and advised by
Paul Reichmann, former head of Olympia &amp; York, yesterday made its first
investment as it paid Dollars 634m (Pounds 419m) for a block of properties
and property loans from Travelers, the US insurer.
Also yesterday, Soros' Quantum Fund revealed a plan to set up a new UK
property fund to take on its interest in a Pounds 500m joint venture with
British Land, the UK property group, which was announced in June.
Shares in the new fund, denominated in sterling, could eventually be listed
separately in London.
The disposal by Travelers marks the insurer's first bulk sale of properties
since an announcement in February that it intended to accelerate the
disposal of Dollars 5bn of underperforming property loans and properties
acquired as a result of defaults on commercial mortgages.
Quantum Realty Fund, the Soros US property fund launched in March, bought 35
properties and 12 commercial mortgage loans, representing 6m square feet of
commercial space and 6,000 residential units.
Travelers said the money raised would be reinvested in higher-yielding
assets, principally corporate, municipal and mortgage-backed bonds. Neither
side would disclose the yield on the underperforming properties, but Mr
Reichmann said the investment brings 'strong current cashflow as well as the
prospect for significant capital appreciation as the property markets
recover later in the decade'.
Quantum Realty will put up around Dollars 210m, with a further Dollars 90m
being provided Mr Soros and various Soros family investment vehicles. The
rest has come from a bridging loan, which will be refinanced by an issue of
mortgage-backed securities. The leverage in the fund could be increased in
the future by a further securitisation in the form of a property investment
trust, Mr Soros said.
Following the Travelers deal, the Quantum Realty Fund will still have
Dollars 500m of equity to invest in properties.
Meanwhile, the Quantum Fund said the plan to spin off its UK property
interests would not alter the terms of its relationship with British Land,
in which the investment fund owns 11m shares.
</TEXT>
