<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / Pru slips to Pounds 242m at halfway stage: Underlying
profits rise 14% - Interim dividend increased 10%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRUDENTIAL Corporation, the UK's largest life insurance company, yesterday
reported an interim profit fall to Pounds 242m from Pounds 249m a year ago,
but said underlying profits rose 14 per cent at current exchange rates.
It raised its interim dividend almost 10 per cent to 4.5p per share. Profits
for the 1992 period were boosted by a one-off gain of Pounds 52m resulting
from a restructuring of assets in the shareholders' portfolio.
The Prudential's general insurance business earned Pounds 18m in the six
months ended June 30, against a loss last time of Pounds 21m. The company's
Mercantile and General Reinsurance business pared its loss to Pounds 7m from
Pounds 25m.
The company has withdrawn from general insurance and has raised premiums in
many of its personal lines. Mr Mick Newmarch, chief executive, said the
company will remain in personal lines. 'We are writing this business to give
us access to UK households so we can sell them long-term business,' Mr
Newmarch said, noting that under half of the Pru's personal lines customers
have long-term savings products.
Profits from long-term investment-related business were flat at Pounds 200m.
The company has set aside an undisclosed sum to cover anticipated bonus
reductions on its with-profits policies which are not set until the
year-end. The Pru and other insurers have cut bonus rates in line with lower
investment returns in recent years and Mr Newmarch has said he believes
further reductions are necessary.
In the UK, which accounts for 80 per cent of the Pru's sales, annual premium
sales subsided reflecting a drop in so-called industrial branch business
which requires house-to-house collections of premiums.
However, single-premium business jumped to Pounds 1.4bn in new business from
just over Pounds 1bn a year ago, largely due to hefty sales of the company's
single-premium with-profits bond, the Prudence Bond.
Mr Newmarch said he believes that the extensive cost-cutting efforts the
company has made in its life division will help it gain market share once
new rules on disclosure take effect next year. 'It's what the new disclosure
regime is all about. You have got to demonstrate value to your customers,'
he said.
Lex, Page 26
