<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / Privatisation of BR will go ahead, MacGregor reaffirms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE determination of the gov-ernment to proceed with the privatisation of
British Rail, despite criticism from some Tory backbenchers, was reaffirmed
last night by Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary.
He clearly indicated that the Commons would be asked to overturn the
amendment made to the railways bill by the House of Lords. The alterations
made by the Lords would permit BR to bid for franchises to operate passenger
services.
The amendment, which the government claims would undermine the whole
franchising process, received favourable comments from Tory backbenchers
representing constituencies in the south-east who are worried about the
implications of privatisation for commuter fares.
With its majority reduced by recent by-election reverses, even a small
rebellion by Tory backbenchers would cause anxiety for the government
because the amendment is certain to have the backing of most opposition MPs.
In a speech to leaders of the CBI last night, Mr MacGregor looked to
individual BR managers to join private-sector interests in the franchising
process.
He forecast that it would bring competition and induce pressures to raise
quality, attract custom, and reduce costs.
Mr MacGregor described franchises as the best way of bringing together the
experience of existing BR managers and the best from the private sector.
He said: 'Each franchisee will have an incentive to improve his efficiency
and profits within the terms of the franchise specification. And he knows he
will have to compete with newcomers at the next franchise round.'
Mr MacGregor maintained that privatisation would create a railway industry
responsive to market forces where previously there had been a bureaucratic
monolith answerable to ministerial or bureaucratic edict.
He suggested that many of the franchises were likely to be owned by
companies or consortia with local and regional interests.
Stressing that bus operators were interested in franchises, Mr MacGregor
said they were 'natural investments for finance or service companies with
strong regional connections'.
</TEXT>
