<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 93 / Arts: Late premiere - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALASTAIR MACAULAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE American writer Jane Bowles (1917-73) wrote just one play, and here it
is, receiving its British premiere, 40 years on.
In the Summer House, colourfully located in southern California, belongs to
the Tennessee Williams tradition of psychological-cum-social drama - a
tradition descending from Ibsen, Chekhov, and Freud. Mainly about the
interior lives of women, it not infrequently recalls the darker paths
investigated in the same postwar period by Martha Graham's psychoanalytic
dance-dramas. We see no less than three mother-daughter pairings, each one
marked by selfishness, intimacy, vulnerability, insensitivity, and
manipulation.
The most 'dramatic' event is a death offstage, and it is Bowles's most
audacious touch to make this occur during Act One. Was it an accident? It is
officially accepted as such by all. But we are never sure; and we keep
watching how the survivors react, months after. Yet Bowles is boldest of all
in not making this death central to anyone's life. This is not a Patricia
Highsmith thriller, where complicity and guilt colour everything. The death
simply intensifies psychological threads that already run through the
characters.
The plot centres on the relationship between the passive, repressed Molly
(in her late teens) and her elegant, controlling mother Gertrude. The summer
house, in Gertrude's garden, is where Molly lingers sullenly: a womb-like
symbol for the prepubescent state of protected dependence which Molly clings
to. It is Molly who may or may not be responsible for the death of a sibling
rival, Vivian Constable. During Act One, both Molly and Gertrude get
married, but, whereas Molly does not want to leave home, her mother is ready
to break from her daughter.
The thrill of Act Two lies in our discovery that, 10 months later, neither
mother nor daughter has really accepted the new men in their lives. Molly
craves her mother and former home; Gertrude uses her daughter in her effort
to flee from wedded non-bliss. All of which is complicated by the eerie
presence of Mrs Constable, mother of the late Vivian. It is she who changes
most during the play - from nervous fusspot, following awkwardly in her
daughter's shadow, to half-crazed drunk, realising in her cups that her
daughter and husband never loved her, tending some of Molly's filial scars.
Derek Goldby's direction of this play at the Lyric Hammersmith has complete
fluency and - thanks also to Hayden Griffin's designs - Californian
atmosphere. Small roles are played with force, wit, and conviction. Only in
Tom Bowles's playing of Molly's husband is there any of the usual British
discomfort with American accents. Gertrude, Molly, Mrs Constable and Vivian
Constable, four tricky roles, are acted by Rosemary Harris, Sophie
Thursfield, Dana Ivey and Robin Weaver with assurance, skill, but not enough
danger. Especially from Harris, who is so nearly a great actress, I wanted
less charm, more edge.
</TEXT>
<XX>
